WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:06.000
Good afternoon, dear colleagues. Today we are going to discuss the topic of the presentation.

00:06.000 --> 00:16.000
I am Alexander Bobkov, business coach. My topic, my specialization is sales, negotiations, presentations, as well as time management and effective business communication.

00:16.000 --> 00:23.000
The topic of the commercial presentation is included in the block on the effective skills of business communication.

00:23.000 --> 00:30.000
Today we will discuss all the necessary elements of preparation and holding a commercial presentation.

00:30.000 --> 00:39.000
First, we will discuss what the concept of the purpose of the presentation is and what the task of the commercial presentation is.

00:39.000 --> 00:54.000
We will consider what actions and stages we are going through in the process of preparing the presentation, in the process of building its structure, in the process of selecting the words and key phrases from which the presentation will consist.

00:54.000 --> 01:12.000
We will consider what ways and methods you can establish contact with the audience, gain understanding, gain trust and do everything necessary for your presentation to achieve its goal, that is, to achieve the perception, attention and understanding of those people to whom it will be addressed.

01:12.000 --> 01:25.000
We will also consider how you can attract, retain and restore the attention of the audience that came to you, came to hear you, see you.

01:25.000 --> 01:41.000
We will also consider how and by what methods you can answer questions that come from the audience, what methods of argumentation to use and how to work with difficult cases, with cases when difficult questions come from the audience that require an answer.

01:41.000 --> 01:50.000
And in conclusion, we will consider how and by what methods we can achieve an effective and effective completion of the presentation.

01:50.000 --> 01:53.000
How often do you have to make presentations?

01:53.000 --> 02:08.000
Probably everyone is different. At some points it requires us to be constantly involved. Sometimes we do it once in a while. In any case, whenever this does not happen, we require extreme concentration and understanding of what we are doing this presentation for.

02:08.000 --> 02:27.000
Any presentation has a purpose. The presentation is addressed to a certain circle of listeners and most likely has a certain topic. Sometimes you can hear and see presentations whose purpose is not clear, whose purpose is not clarified even by the speaker himself.

02:28.000 --> 02:41.000
The presentation is in the form of information, a collection of information that ends with the words, well, that's probably all, I said everything I wanted, the rest is at the discretion of the listeners.

02:41.000 --> 03:05.000
Your presentation, the presentation of the commercial plan, should have a completely specific goal. Make some changes, make some shift, plan some action and encourage those people who listen to you, those people who came to you for the presentation, those people whom you address with your informational message and whom you address with your convincing influence.

03:05.000 --> 03:32.000
Plan a specific result and your presentation will achieve the goal for which it was created. It is also important to understand that the goal of the presentation is not the goal itself, it is part of the solution to some larger task, some basic task. And having received the result of a specific presentation, you then, apparently, use this result, this solution to achieve a higher goal, a larger-scale goal.

03:32.000 --> 03:51.000
It is important to clearly understand how the result of your presentation will be used. It is important to understand how you will build it into the general context of your activity. This result should be interesting not only to you, of course, you mean your benefit or the benefit of those whom you represent at the presentation.

03:51.000 --> 04:06.000
It is also important to ensure that this goal, this benefit, is interesting to the audience. In this case, the audience will be faster, easier and more eager to follow you and respond to your call to encourage action.

04:21.000 --> 04:38.000
We all saw the weather forecast on TV. We see it every day. What do we hear? What do we see? A person speaks, he gives information, he gives information, he gives a weather forecast. Is this a presentation? Yes, to some extent it is.

04:38.000 --> 04:58.000
We receive information, but at the same time we do not get any motivation to act. This is the first, the very initial level of the presentation. The presentation is just for information. Here is a minimal direction to the belief and also a small direction to the information. Just give information.

04:58.000 --> 05:17.000
Another kind of presentation is when we see a candidate's speech at some elections, when we see a person who is burning with some idea and trying to convey this idea to the audience, to the public. And not just to convey this idea, but to infect it, to ignite the public.

05:17.000 --> 05:40.000
Again, I mean some kind of goal. In this case, in the case of a pre-election speech, to gather as many supporters as possible, to attract as many votes as possible at the elections. In this case, the informative part is small, but there is a great deal of impact, a great deal of desire to convince, a great deal of emotional message.

05:41.000 --> 05:56.000
The third case is when we see, for example, a commercial presentation of a person selling a product. In this case, we see a great deal of belief, a desire to sell a product, a desire to present in the best light all the characteristics, advantages and benefits of this product.

05:56.000 --> 06:18.000
And there is also a large and capacious informational part that allows the client, the potential buyer, to learn more and better about the product. All together creates a strong, bright, juicy and attractive picture. All together creates a picture of a commercial presentation that is filled with informational impact and convincing power.

06:19.000 --> 06:40.000
And the fourth version of the presentation, when we see, for example, a working meeting of a project group, when colleagues meet, who set their goal to inform each other about the state of affairs, about the position of things in the project. At the same time, they do not have any task to convince each other in any matter, they just inform.

06:41.000 --> 06:59.000
Different presentations, different degrees of combination of information and belief factors. We need to understand what our presentation will be about, what it will be aimed at. Will it be more aimed at informing people? Or is our task to convince, shift the point of view, help people understand something else?

06:59.000 --> 07:10.000
As soon as we determine this for ourselves, it will become clear to us how to prepare our presentation and what words, key phrases, actions we should put into it.

07:11.000 --> 07:27.000
For us, it is also important to analyze those people, the audience that will meet us in the hall. It is important for us to understand who is in the hall, it is important for us to understand for whom we will speak. Why is this important? Because different people perceive the information that we give in different ways.

07:27.000 --> 07:50.000
What is important to know about those people who are waiting for us in the audience? First, age and gender. Second, what social group do they belong to? Third, what interests do most of them pursue? And, perhaps, it is worth analyzing and foreseeing what their emotional state is at the moment of your appearance in the audience.

07:51.000 --> 08:04.000
The fact is that these factors are very important, because they affect the perception of the information that you are going to convey to the audience. It is important to take into account the characteristics of the audience when preparing your speech.

08:05.000 --> 08:17.000
Experts in the perception of a person have established that the best time to speak in front of young people, as well as elderly people and women, is in the evening, and most likely late in the evening.

08:18.000 --> 08:35.000
Because at this time, a person has the most developed perception of the emotional aspects of the speech. And there is a place for a variety of stories from life, there is a place for appeals to feelings, there is a place for stories about what you felt and what you were experiencing at that particular moment.

08:35.000 --> 09:01.000
It is good to address emotions at this moment. The morning time is also optimal for speaking in front of those people who are men in their mid-life, who have a well-developed rational side of perception. And the morning hours, the daytime hours, are a good time to provide facts, arguments, statistics, numbers, diagrams, demonstration of specific data on the studies, tests, and so on.

09:02.000 --> 09:18.000
So, we know who we are speaking in front of, we have planned the time of the speech, we imagine what we want to say. It is time to prepare for the presentation, it is time to go through the important three stages, three components of preparation.

09:18.000 --> 09:43.000
Imagine that you have to make a film, literally make a film about yourself. What is done first of all before making a film? The film is created on the basis of some literary work or script. It is important for us to write a script, it is important for us to put all these words into it, the main ones, the important ones, which must necessarily be voiced in front of our audience.

09:43.000 --> 10:01.000
The first stage is the lexical structure of the presentation. It is a verbal frame, it is a skeleton, if you want, on which we can then hang all the necessary components of the presentation.

10:01.000 --> 10:28.000
The second step is to understand at what point and in what sequence the following phrases, arguments, conclusions, some stories will be voiced. It is important for us to make a compositional plan of our presentation. The compositional plan includes the introduction, the introduction, then the main part, and then the conclusion. Each of these parts takes a certain time.

10:28.000 --> 10:47.000
In addition, it is important to predict how we will distribute our efforts during the presentation. At what point will we talk about one topic, at what point will we move on to another, how much time will we devote to some specific fact, how much time will we devote to each slide, if we use slides in the presentation.

10:47.000 --> 11:12.000
It is not a secret that before the presentation, each of us experiences some excitement, experiences a small amount of adrenaline. In this case, preparation is the best way to cope with such excitement, because preparation offers you clear knowledge of what you will talk about, in what sequence and how much time you will have for each logical and thematic block.

11:12.000 --> 11:38.000
In order to build a plan of the lexical structure of the presentation, it is important for you to understand what exactly the words you want to say to your audience. What will these words be about? It is important to plan, write down what should be voiced in your presentation, what are the main points, what are the facts, what arguments should be there so that the audience, hearing them, can make a decision on the results of the presentation easier.

11:39.000 --> 11:55.000
Any literary work is built according to the law of composition. Where does any book start? Does the main character take action immediately? No. First, we see the prologue, the description of events, the description of the situation in which the main part will unfold.

11:55.000 --> 12:14.000
Then the events begin, which make up the main part of the book. And somewhere in this book there is a shot, a decisive action is made, what is the basis, the culmination of the whole plot. Then follows the epilogue, that is, the exit from the situation, the conclusion.

12:14.000 --> 12:31.000
Your presentation can also be built according to the law of composition, according to the laws of the literary genre, according to the laws of creativity. After all, a strange-looking orator, a presenter, who, jumping on stage, immediately begins to tell something to those who have gathered about the product or their point of view.

12:44.000 --> 13:04.000
And then he will begin to talk about the properties, advantages, his point of view, what the audience needs, what are its benefits. In this case, it is important to understand that any process that we perform from the stage as a presenter can and should be built according to the law of composition.

13:04.000 --> 13:18.000
So, you know who is in the hall, you have built your presentation, you know what you will say and in what sequence. It is also important for you to understand how much time you will devote to each meaningful and logical block. The recommendations are as follows.

13:18.000 --> 13:42.000
Give no more than 20 minutes to one big topic. More time will simply not be perceived. Your audience will most likely get tired of listening to the same thing over and over again for more than 20 minutes. Change the topic, move on to the next question, change the style of presentation, change the form of presentation, change something every 20 minutes.

13:42.000 --> 14:11.000
It is also important to remember that one logical block, one part of the topic can be in the focus of attention for no more than 6 minutes. After 6 minutes, make a logical pause, draw attention to something, make a change so that people's perception is refreshed and they can see something new in the topic you are discussing from a different point of view.

14:12.000 --> 14:32.000
And if you use slides, spend no more than 3 minutes to consider each topic on each slide. 3 minutes is the limit for which the slide attracts attention. After 3 minutes, it is important to change the slide and move on to the next block of consideration of your topic.

14:32.000 --> 14:59.000
How important are the first seconds of your appearance in front of the audience? This is the golden time, these are the seconds during which you make the first impression on your audience. Of course, it is very desirable that this impression is favorable. This is the basis of your performance. Many presentations fail in these seconds. And also many presentations are made in the first seconds of your appearance.

14:59.000 --> 15:15.000
Why is this so? Because in these seconds people make the first impression on you, and then it acts during the entire presentation. The audience projects the impression you made during the first seconds of your appearance on you.

15:15.000 --> 15:40.000
What is the most important thing to consider in these initial and very important moments of the presentation? First, how you appear, how you come to your audience. It is no secret that the components of the first impression include several factors. We receive information on different channels. And the most powerful of them, the biggest, is the channel of visual perception.

15:40.000 --> 16:09.000
We all know this proverb. And the appearance of a new person in front of us is perceived primarily by what we see. And what do we see? How he is dressed, how he looks, how he moves, how he walks, how he looks, how he holds his head. There are many different details, many different moments that attract our attention, and we perceive them as a whole. We make the first impression on how a person moves.

16:10.000 --> 16:34.000
Your appearance to the audience is your self-presentation. It is how you hold yourself, how you behave in these minutes. Getting out of the table, getting up from the hall to the stage, getting out of the backstage. All these are golden seconds that largely determine how the audience will perceive you.

16:35.000 --> 16:51.000
When you go out to the audience, to those people who were waiting for you, it is important to take a short pause, not to rush into battle right away, not to start talking as soon as you appeared on stage. Take a few seconds of pause. For what?

16:51.000 --> 17:16.000
In order to get acquainted with the audience, in order to establish a so-called visual contact, it is enough to just run through the eyes, stopping at each one for no more than half a second. Those people who respond to your gaze, just thank them with your eyes, say hello with your eyes. Those who have not yet seen you, just miss.

17:16.000 --> 17:31.000
It is important to find several allies in the hall, several people who are already ready to perceive you. In the future, you will be able to use this support to melt the ice of the whole hall, if not all people have yet paid attention to you.

17:31.000 --> 17:54.000
Visual contact is a confirmation of your status. You went on stage, you take the situation into your hands, you show who came. And then the words of greeting follow, then the words that can have different meanings in one. You start talking, you turn on the audio channel of perception for your listeners.

17:55.000 --> 18:08.000
Our speech consists of two important components. Firstly, this is a vocal channel, that is, a channel that reflects the voice characteristics of speech. The tone, the volume, the intonation, the pace of speech.

18:08.000 --> 18:22.000
Secondly, this is the meaning of the words. The channel is called verbal. It is important to understand that in the first seconds the greatest emphasis, the greatest attention is paid to the voice characteristics of speech, to how you speak.

18:22.000 --> 18:38.000
And here, perhaps, the richest and most important component for change is the intonation component. The intonation with which you go to the audience, how you greet it. What intonation will be optimal in this case for greeting?

18:38.000 --> 18:56.000
It is important to understand what kind of audience you are speaking to. If the audience is business, that is, people who are going to receive information, who are going to make a rational decision, most likely a neutral business will suit, but at the same time dynamic, filled with enthusiasm, intonation.

18:56.000 --> 19:10.000
If you speak in front of an audience of people who prefer an emotional type of speech, most likely a warmer, more intense, more provocative speech, contact and intonation are needed.

19:10.000 --> 19:31.000
Greetings, in addition to your self-presentation, in addition to the reflection of your emotional state in the form of intonation, also carry the function of creating a certainty. You greet the audience, you say who you are, you name the topic of the speech, and the audience becomes more clear who is who.

19:31.000 --> 19:45.000
The roles are determined, you are the presenter, the audience is the listener. More certainty is created and the center of this certainty is you. You helped the audience feel themselves in their place and now you will start your presentation.

19:45.000 --> 20:01.000
Also, at the beginning of the presentation, you can make a small action that will help you feel like the host of the situation. The feeling of the host on stage is an important condition of the presenter, because it is in his hands that the management of the whole situation is.

20:01.000 --> 20:17.000
At the beginning of the presentation, you can make a simple action. Ask the audience about something that will allow them to raise their hands, ask who came to the subway today, raise your hands, the audience will respond.

20:17.000 --> 20:35.000
Ask someone to move the table, turn on the light, fix the glass on the windows. Any action that is carried out at your request already shows that you have control over the situation here and the situation of managing the presentation is in your hands.

20:35.000 --> 20:49.000
Speaking of a commercial presentation, it is important to remember about the structure that will help you achieve your goals and lead the audience to make a decision. This structure consists of four steps. The first of them is to attract attention.

20:49.000 --> 21:05.000
It is important at the beginning of the presentation to set a topic, a direction of conversation that will be interesting to the audience, which will attract it and make it pay attention to what you say. Attracting attention is the first step in the presentation structure.

21:05.000 --> 21:20.000
Then it is important to make everything necessary for the audience to have an interest in what you offer, what you tell, what you sell. Attracting interest is the second step in the structure of a commercial presentation.

21:20.000 --> 21:36.000
The next step is to arouse the desire of people to take advantage of what you offer, to buy what you sell, to arouse emotional feelings in them, to arouse a desire, motivation to purchase or use your goods or services.

21:36.000 --> 21:56.000
And at the end of the presentation, it is necessary to do everything so that people take action, go and buy, vote, decide and do what you offer. It is important to include in the conclusion of the presentation the encouraging moment, the words that encourage the audience to act.

21:56.000 --> 22:04.000
Of course, you encourage the audience to take action that is beneficial to you and to those whom you represent by conducting a commercial presentation.

22:04.000 --> 22:17.000
How to attract the audience's attention at the very beginning? What to start with so that all the views of those sitting in the conference room are addressed to you? What techniques, what methods can be used?

22:18.000 --> 22:40.000
First, you can start with some kind of statement. For example, you know, I have one question that I suppose not many of you here will answer affirmatively. And perhaps this will attract more views if you started with a presentation that does not concern everyone in the conference room.

22:41.000 --> 23:02.000
You can start with some fresh news on the topic of the presentation. If you speak in front of a company that works in a certain industry, it may be interesting to hear some fresh report from the State Commissariat on this market. It may be interesting to hear the news from the industry exhibition or the release of some new product under the brand of a well-known brand.

23:03.000 --> 23:13.000
This news will also attract attention, will allow you to collect views, to collect the focus of the audience's attention, and then to make a bridge to move on to the topic you wanted to talk about in the presentation.

23:14.000 --> 23:34.000
The beginning that attracts attention can also be considered a dramatic beginning, when you intentionally, deliberately emphasizing the words, start the presentation. For example, in this case, ladies and gentlemen, the topic of the presentation is important to all of us today, this topic, and then you announce the topic.

23:34.000 --> 24:03.000
Intentional emphasis allows to attract the attention of those who are going to the presentation. Or you can start the presentation with a ball throw, throw the topic into the audience, say, for example, you know, before the presentation I talked to some of the participants and met with different points of view, help me figure it out, I heard about this one and also heard another, what point of view of your audience will be correct.

24:04.000 --> 24:15.000
Perhaps the participants will be able to respond to this discussion, and then you can direct this discussion to the right course, asking the topic that was planned as a topic of the presentation.

24:15.000 --> 24:27.000
The main thing in the management of attention is the following. It is important to constantly vary the focus of attention, change it, surprise with something sometimes, and keep the attention that you won at the very beginning.

24:28.000 --> 24:40.000
The presentation that you make in front of the audience is not so prepared for your speech, and perhaps some controversial questions, objections will be met sometimes with questions.

24:41.000 --> 24:48.000
Sometimes you will hear objections to your address, acute questions that will require from you, concentration, cold blood and endurance.

24:49.000 --> 24:59.000
How to work with objections that are voiced in the presentation? First, let your opponent, the person speaking, to speak out completely.

25:00.000 --> 25:10.000
For this person, the question he is talking about is important, he is emotionally touched by it, and it is important that the person expresses himself in this emotion completely, that he says everything he wants to say.

25:11.000 --> 25:23.000
Even if you already have a ready answer to this question, which you may have heard repeatedly in this composition, let the person speak out, finish the question to the end. This is an important condition.

25:23.000 --> 25:35.000
Then, having asked again, clarify the understanding of the question. Perhaps it is even worth rephrasing the question so that it takes on the form, the appearance in which you will work more comfortably with it.

25:36.000 --> 25:48.000
Rephrase, clarify the understanding, ask the question for understanding. I understand you correctly, you mean this and that. And ask the question in the form that is most convenient for you.

25:49.000 --> 26:06.000
And then express your understanding and acceptance of the situation. Expressing understanding does not mean agreeing with the objector. It is important to admit that such a point of view, such a view of the problem, such an opinion simply takes place.

26:06.000 --> 26:13.000
Such a point of view can exist and it is normal. You express your acceptance and understanding of this fact.

26:14.000 --> 26:30.000
Then, when you have joined this expression, joined the understanding of this question, you can give this information, facts, arguments that help your opponent understand that you have this information and are ready to respond to objections.

26:30.000 --> 26:41.000
What is the effectiveness, what is the benefit of such a method of working with objections? It is important to understand that we do not argue with the opponent, we do not try to convince him that we are right.

26:42.000 --> 26:59.000
We accept his point of view and share information, acting as allies. Thus, if we have processed the objection correctly, most likely this person will understand that we are not tuned to the battle, not tuned to the conflict and ready to work constructively, sharing information, helping to better understand.

27:00.000 --> 27:04.000
