27:05.000 --> 27:17.000
In the case when we need to prove something, in the case when we have arguments that confirm the facts we have said in the presentation, it is important to comply with some important requirements when selecting these arguments.

27:17.000 --> 27:30.000
First, the argument must be verified, its credibility must be indisputable, it must be of those that do not require special evidence and most likely will be accepted at once.

27:31.000 --> 27:39.000
It is good to indicate the source from which you have this information, from where you got this information, what helped you to make sure of the credibility of this argument.

27:39.000 --> 27:57.000
The argument is an influence directed at the point of view, but not the opponent. The opponent who expresses an objection, he just shares his point of view with you. Therefore, there should be nothing personal in the argument, directed at the person with whom you communicate, arguing some point of view.

27:57.000 --> 28:13.000
It is good if the argument is confirmed by some visual evidence, it is confirmed by graphs, numbers, diagrams, illustrations, if there is some plot showing that the argument is credible, if there is some video recording, it is great.

28:13.000 --> 28:36.000
The clarity helps to make sure that this argument is reliable and can be trusted. If you communicate with an audience that is not specialists in the field you are talking about, it is good to use a language free of terms, special words, various professional terms, use an accessible language so that people have a complete understanding of what you are talking about.

28:36.000 --> 29:05.000
Sometimes you can decode the terms you use so that they are understood by the audience, and then use the terms that are already decoded in your presentation. In order to show the audience the meaning of these terms, it is enough to decode them once, show their meaning, perhaps give some examples, demonstrations, illustrations. This will help the audience later to perceive the terms as understandable to them.

29:06.000 --> 29:21.000
One more rule about arguments. Declare them as the degree of strength increases. From strong to stronger and finally to the strongest. So that the audience remembers the argument that was the strongest. It will sound at the end.

29:21.000 --> 29:34.000
So, having gone through the stages of the introduction, the main part, and approaching the conclusion, it is important to summarize, it is important to complete the presentation in such a way that it helps to achieve the set goal.

29:51.000 --> 30:04.000
It is important to show that the situation that is important, which requires intervention, which requires decisions, to show that the offer of your presentation will help to solve this situation, will help to cope with the tasks that are in front of the audience.

30:04.000 --> 30:26.000
And give perspective, give a bridge to the future, show how the adoption of a specific decision by the audience will help it in the future, will help it either avoid something or achieve something. So that the audience understands how the decision made today will affect the situation in the future, will affect their life, their well-being, their well-being.

30:26.000 --> 30:50.000
And the fourth step is the most important. Make an encouraging impact, encourage the audience to specific actions. Say literally, so buy, so buy, use, win, vote, or whatever you want to say. It is important that the audience hears this not as an opportunity, but as a call, as an encouragement to action.

30:50.000 --> 31:13.000
Complete the presentation on an emotional rise. This is important to summarize, because the presentation is remembered by the last words, by the last gestures. It is remembered that the presenter made a farewell. Make a striking performance, make a performance on a rise. Show the audience that you leave it filled with energy and enthusiasm, so that the audience remembers you in this way.

