It is also important that the goal is specific, that it is measurable, if possible. For example, increase sales by 30%. This is the correct formulation of the goal. If you are thinking about how to sell more by the end of the negotiations, this goal is not specific and, most likely, it needs to be concretized, that is, expressed in a specific figure, in an exact figure, the increase of what, the growth of what and how much you want to achieve as a result of the negotiations you have conducted.

35:31.000 --> 35:45.000
Defining the goals of the negotiations for ourselves, we must also understand what tasks we must solve, building up the negotiation process with our counteragents. We need to understand what tasks will be solved as a result of these negotiations.

35:45.000 --> 36:07.000
The tasks may concern both business relations and business results. We need to understand what we want to achieve first, what we want to achieve second, and what we should also worry about third. For example, it may be that the main task of these negotiations will be to conclude a contract with some company.

36:07.000 --> 36:34.000
At the same time, the task of the second level will be to maintain partnership for the next period. And the task of the third level is to create prerequisites for signing a more significant, larger contract next year with this company, based on several years of full-fledged cooperation. That is, each task that is solved in the negotiation process may concern both the present time and the time in the future.

36:34.000 --> 37:01.000
It is also important for us to understand how the task that we solve in the negotiation process takes into account the interests of the other party. It is important for us to assume what the other party will get in return, how its interests will be taken into account, if the task of the negotiations is fulfilled, is solved. This will help us avoid pulling the blanket over ourselves when we only mean our interests and do not care that the interests of the other party are also observed.

37:01.000 --> 37:22.000
And when we are setting up a negotiation task, we need to understand what task of a higher level will help us to achieve the success of specific negotiations. If we return from negotiations with the result we have achieved, where do we then put this result? What task of a higher level will help us to achieve the result of the negotiations we have achieved?

37:31.000 --> 37:51.000
First, it is important to clearly define the needs of each party from the very beginning. Of course, we know our needs clearly. It is also important to assume what interests the mutual party pursues, what interests our opponent, the partner in negotiations pursues.

38:01.000 --> 38:24.000
And to motivate him to sign the contract, taking into account what the other party wants as a result of the negotiations. It is also important for us to foresee how and in what ways we can satisfy our needs and offer ways to satisfy the needs of the other party in exchange for some mutual concessions in our favor.

38:24.000 --> 38:49.000
It is important to prepare several options in advance for how this or that goal of the negotiations will be achieved. What are the possibilities? What are the options? What can be done differently? What can be done taking into account the changing situation? So that the other party understands that we do not mean only one option to satisfy our needs, but also think about the ways that will help the other party achieve its results.

38:49.000 --> 39:03.000
In preparation for a proposal on specific issues, it is important for us to understand what objective criteria are there for making a decision on this issue. It is important to understand what norms, what stereotypes correspond to a particular decision.

39:03.000 --> 39:24.000
If, for example, we are trying to make a decision on some issue, we mean the range within which the decision on this issue will be considered normal. For example, we offer our partner to increase the number of supplied products by 20%. At the same time, we understand that the supply within this figure is normal.

39:25.000 --> 39:44.000
We do not require more, we do not require to increase the supply by 50%, because objective criteria show us that this kind of supply is not possible for our partner. He simply will not have time to produce such a quantity. Therefore, we can insist on and offer this kind of increase as a normal increase that fits into the objective criteria on this issue.

39:44.000 --> 40:03.000
It is important to be ready in the negotiation process for the emergence of alternative solutions, for the emergence of a situation in which the decision you propose will seem unacceptable to the other party, for example, due to some changed circumstances, due to reasons that you did not know about before the negotiations.

40:03.000 --> 40:20.000
It is important to foresee this and to offer the other party an alternative solution that will allow you to show your readiness to act even in a changed situation. And the other party, having assessed this, will be able to develop a solution for itself according to your proposal.

40:20.000 --> 40:41.000
And a good support in the solution of the purpose of the negotiations will be an option to achieve an agreement, a contract, a protocol on intentions, some formulation that will be offered to you as a product, as a result of this negotiation session, which can be agreed upon, changed, supplemented with some considerations of the other party.

40:42.000 --> 40:54.000
But the framework, the template and your proposal, the option of agreement, will be for you, and this will also be assessed by the other party as readiness to conduct a negotiation process at a high professional level.

40:54.000 --> 41:01.000
Tell me, when did you hold the last negotiations? What were the negotiations like? With whom? On what basis?

41:01.000 --> 41:14.000
You probably remember your feelings from the first meeting with this person, with this party, and you remember what you may have lacked in these negotiations to achieve the important and necessary goal.

41:14.000 --> 41:24.000
And maybe everything went well and you achieved what you wanted and got it knowing why, knowing what helped you and what influenced the outcome of these negotiations.

41:24.000 --> 41:36.000
What qualities, what sides of the personality, what characteristics of the negotiator influence the outcome of negotiations in one way or another? What qualities help to achieve success in negotiations?

41:36.000 --> 41:50.000
First, it is purposefulness, a clear vision, a clear format of the goal, a clear understanding of what I am going to achieve, what I want to achieve, what result I need as a result of these negotiations.

41:50.000 --> 42:06.000
And no matter what happens, no matter what the topic is, no matter which way your interlocutor is distracted, you always know what to look for, what channel to follow, what course to follow and which way to move the negotiation process.

42:06.000 --> 42:16.000
This is your goal, the goal that you planned in advance, outlined and even wrote down for yourself in order to remember what goal is in front of you in these negotiations.

42:17.000 --> 42:29.000
Secondly, the hardness of the ability to resist pressure and, perhaps, the same professional approach to negotiating that another country uses is important.

42:29.000 --> 42:42.000
The hardness of the ability to defend your position, the hardness of the belief that the position you are defending is correct and can be accepted as the starting point for the completion of negotiations.

42:42.000 --> 43:06.000
And also, a successful negotiator requires patience, the ability to look for, study, learn alternative points of view, alternative ways to solve problems, and to consider possible ways of satisfaction for both yourself and your mutual benefit.

43:07.000 --> 43:14.000
What qualities can interfere? What barriers are in the way to success in negotiations?

43:14.000 --> 43:24.000
First, it is the expectation of the obvious. When negotiating, it is important to be prepared for the fact that they may not go as you imagine.

43:24.000 --> 43:34.000
Another country may propose some other proposals, it may propose some other solutions to the problems discussed in the negotiations.

43:34.000 --> 43:41.000
Anything can happen, including the fact that the person you expected will not appear at the negotiations, but another representative of the company.

43:41.000 --> 43:53.000
The agenda of the day may change, the place of the negotiations may change. It is important to be prepared for the fact that you will have to achieve your goals in different circumstances, in different conditions, with another person.

43:53.000 --> 44:03.000
This kind of flexibility and readiness, openness to new things, openness to change in the situation, helps to keep your lines and achieve success in negotiations.

44:03.000 --> 44:15.000
Barriers to success in negotiations also include self-doubt, the lack of confidence that I have the right to claim and insist on taking my point of view.

44:15.000 --> 44:30.000
Self-confidence is an important part of the negotiation process. You may be tested, you may be checked, you may be pushed by another country in order to achieve your goal in negotiations.

44:30.000 --> 44:39.000
Self-confidence is a way to resist pressure, it is a way to insist on taking your point of view, a way to achieve your goal in negotiations.

44:39.000 --> 44:55.000
The third barrier to success in negotiations is conformity, that is, the desire to comply with some norms, rules, the desire to arrange everything in order to take the point of view offered by the other side.

44:55.000 --> 45:12.000
In negotiations, conformity is unacceptable. It is important to understand that, of course, compromises can be made, it is important to take the opinion of the other side into account, but it is not worth striving for taking another point of view without a contract and not insisting on mutual concessions.

45:12.000 --> 45:28.000
What is the basis of negotiations? How does the theater start? The negotiations start with the meeting of two people who, of course, first of all, evaluate each other. Two people meet and evaluate each other, first of all, on the external signs.

45:28.000 --> 45:41.000
The first seconds, the first meeting, a handshake, and two people immediately make an opinion of each other. What impression would you like to make on your opponent, on your partner in negotiations?

45:41.000 --> 46:03.000
Most likely, he will be able to understand that in front of him is a respectable person, serious, knowledgeable and striving to achieve the agreements that represent the company, the side that has weight, has respect, respects itself and is ready to negotiate with the same partners.

46:03.000 --> 46:19.000
Everything is important here. The appearance is important, the clothes, accessories, the state of the clothes, the state of your hairstyle, the state of your face, even the smell from your mouth is also important.

46:19.000 --> 46:34.000
It is important that no detail contradicts the composition of your presentation as a person who is successful, who represents a successful company, while being ready to go to negotiations, ready to discuss, consider various points of view.

46:34.000 --> 46:51.000
In addition to the appearance, the nature of the gestures and movements that you make from the very beginning is also important. Even those movements that you make towards your partner in negotiations are already being evaluated by him, he already makes an impression, makes an idea of ​​you.

46:51.000 --> 47:09.000
How do you go? Confidently, waving, looking ahead, or are you going without confidence, as if you were visiting? From this moment on, your party can determine for itself what position it will take in negotiations. Your party will understand what is to be done.

47:09.000 --> 47:23.000
It is important to find a compromise, or you can sit down, push, use your weakness and self-doubt, if it is there, if it is seen. Your pose and facial expression, your facial expression, also play a big role.

47:23.000 --> 47:45.000
If we talk about negotiations while standing, then it is important that you take an open position in relation to the side with which you are negotiating. This means not to cross your hands, not to close your limbs, keep your head straight, turn your shoulders and show with all your appearance that you are ready for contact, ready for dialogue, ready to negotiate.

47:45.000 --> 47:57.000
In this case, even if you are sitting, it is important to keep your back straight so that your partner understands that you are ready, you are in the right tone, you are ready to have effective and effective negotiations.

47:57.000 --> 48:07.000
What should the negotiator's facial expression be like? Most likely, it should be such that your partner understands that you are an open, safe person and are able to experience some emotions.

48:07.000 --> 48:33.000
Of course, the face should not resemble a mask, a frozen mask that does not reflect anything. Although, on the other hand, in the case when you participate in negotiations on issues important to you and important to your partner, the face should be under control and not express some joy about what has happened, some dismay about the argument heard.

48:33.000 --> 48:41.000
In these cases, the face should accept the usual expression of a benevolent readiness for dialogue, for the negotiation process.

48:41.000 --> 48:56.000
In addition to the appearance, in addition to the characteristics that can be observed, your partner also evaluates you in terms of how your voice sounds. And here we can divide the voice into several components.

48:56.000 --> 49:13.000
What is considered in negotiations? What does your partner hear? He hears your tone, he hears your intonation, he hears the tone of speech, he perceives the volume of the voice and he also perceives your diction.

49:13.000 --> 49:30.000
As for each of the components of the voice, you can give several recommendations. If we are talking about intonation, then intonation should express your attitude, your emotional state, express your position on a particular issue.

49:30.000 --> 49:53.000
A passionate monotone voice in negotiations will most likely be perceived as the voice of a person who does not own the situation and does not express a personal attitude to it. In the case when you color your voice and your speech intonationally, the interlocutor's perception is tuned to you as well as to the person who represents the company, but also has a personal attitude to the issue.

49:53.000 --> 50:11.000
As for the volume of the voice, the optimum volume is not perceived as a pressure, not perceived as a pressure. The volume should be such that a person sitting in two steps from where you are sitting or standing in the middle of a conversation can easily hear it.

50:11.000 --> 50:35.000
Speaking of the volume of speech, we must also link this with the characteristics of diction. The standard volume of speech, which is optimal for the average human brain, is 250-270 words per minute. Pronunciation at this rate guarantees that not a single word from your speech will be lost and your interlocutor will catch and hear each of the words you have spoken.

50:35.000 --> 50:54.000
It is important to remember that voice characteristics provide good diction even at a high pace of speech. If your pace is excessive, if the dictionary component suffers, it is better to slow down so that each word is clearly heard and your interlocutor does not have trouble understanding you.

50:54.000 --> 51:21.000
And last but not least, your interlocutor pays attention to the meaning of the words you say. At the first minute, this is not so important, at the first minute, it is most likely that the attention is paid to the voice characteristics, but then, of course, it all depends on how you arrange your negotiations, how you arrange the meaning of the sentences that you address to the opposing party.

51:21.000 --> 51:33.000
When preparing for negotiations, choose which strategy you will take in relation to your opponent. There are probably four strategies, four choices of tactics in your negotiations.

51:33.000 --> 51:50.000
The first strategy is to say, I won, he lost. In this case, we assume that we will try to make our decision, the decision that we propose as a result of the negotiations, be adopted in all possible ways and methods.

51:50.000 --> 52:11.000
At the same time, we will not care that the other party achieves the options that would satisfy it. It is important to understand that by achieving such a temporary advantage, even if our other party accepts the decision we propose, we can lose in the long run.

52:11.000 --> 52:33.000
We can lose a valuable partner, a valuable opponent, lose in relations. And such a position, if it is engaged from the very beginning of the negotiations, rarely leads to a constructive decision. It is rare for a party to fully agree to what the other party offers it and does not require any mutual concessions.

52:34.000 --> 52:50.000
The second strategy is to say, I lost, he won. In this case, we choose a strategy of concessions, a strategy of following the course outlined by your opponent. And this choice can be made only in one case.

52:50.000 --> 53:11.000
When you clearly understand why you make this concession, what you allow your opponent to win, what further steps follow, how you use this temporary concession, this help to your opponent so that he gets what he needs at this moment as a result of the negotiations.

53:12.000 --> 53:33.000
The third strategy is, I lost, he lost. This strategy is not often perceived as a plan of negotiations, it is not consciously chosen. However, it is rather a product, a fruit of the attitude to negotiations as a competition, when each party strives to get a 100% result.

53:33.000 --> 53:55.000
In this case, it all ends with the two parties diverging without achieving any agreement. It is considered normal when each party seeks to make a decision that meets their interests by 80%. It is very rare that both parties get exactly what they wanted at 100%.

53:55.000 --> 54:06.000
If the ratio of 80 to 80 is observed, then in this case the maximum satisfaction of each party is guaranteed by what they achieved in negotiations.

54:07.000 --> 54:24.000
And the fourth strategy is, I won, he won. This is the most optimal strategy that allows you to achieve a compromise, that allows you to achieve that each party gets what it wants. At the same time, it is important that each party gets exactly what is valuable to it.

54:25.000 --> 54:41.000
And here it is possible to have a bargaining, it is possible to have a positional negotiation, or it is possible to find a compromise on some fundamental issues, when the parties make mutual concessions to each other, sacrificing what is not so valuable to them.

54:41.000 --> 54:52.000
But for the other party, it is valuable, important, and it is happy to accept this concession, sacrificing in return what is not so important to it, but is important to the other party.

54:53.000 --> 55:09.000
In any case, it is important to understand that a mutual win lays the foundation for a more dense, longer-term and mutually beneficial cooperation, rather than when we strive for our own win, but do not provide benefits and advantages for the other party.

55:09.000 --> 55:19.000
What role can a negotiator play in the negotiation process? What can he strive for in the negotiation process? What tactics should be used?

55:19.000 --> 55:30.000
It all depends on how much and how we want to combine the ratio of two important factors. First, this is a business result, and secondly, this is a result in the form of relations.

55:31.000 --> 55:44.000
If for us the most important thing is to maintain relations with the other party, and the business result is not so important to us, then our role can be close to the role that is described in the words of self-kindness,

55:45.000 --> 55:55.000
when we are ready to sacrifice part of the business result in order to maintain relations with the other party and arrange the negotiation process in such a way that the relations are in the foreground.

55:55.000 --> 56:08.000
We show our opponent that we are ready to make concessions in order to maintain relations, partnership, and the style of cooperation that was in the work of our companies.

56:09.000 --> 56:22.000
If we believe that there is no point in looking for a compromise in the form of relations or business results, then the style can be close to the style described in the words of an analyst.

56:22.000 --> 56:33.000
We just consider what options and results can be beneficial to us and we lead our policy in order to help the other party to accept this point of view.

56:34.000 --> 56:42.000
But at the same time, neither relations nor relations are too important to us, and at the same time we are not so focused on the business result.

56:43.000 --> 56:55.000
If we are primarily interested in the business result and the relationship is not important to us, then the role of such a position can be close to the role described in the words of the godfather,

56:56.000 --> 57:03.000
a person who cares about the result, a person who cares about the business result, sometimes even to the detriment of relations.

57:04.000 --> 57:09.000
Relations built on competition provide exactly this kind of position.

57:10.000 --> 57:14.000
We strive to get the result at almost any cost, sometimes even at the cost of relations.

57:15.000 --> 57:20.000
And if we are ready for this, then our role is close to the position described by the godfather.

57:20.000 --> 57:32.000
And yet the most optimal, the most reasonable and the most productive position is the position called virtuoso, when we strive to take into account,

57:33.000 --> 57:43.000
strive to achieve the interests of both our country and the country of our opponent, our partner, when we care about the country of relations and care about the business result.

57:44.000 --> 57:51.000
It is important to remember that these two factors are closely interconnected, and if we take care of relations with our country today,

57:52.000 --> 57:57.000
perhaps tomorrow it will be the basis for obtaining a more complete, more substantial business result.

57:58.000 --> 58:08.000
And also cooperation in the business sphere, more close, more dense, helps to build relations that will later become the basis for some new contracts, deals, projects.

58:09.000 --> 58:17.000
Perhaps the fifth position is also intermediate, when we strive to find literally in all the compromise, to reach some middle ground.

58:18.000 --> 58:24.000
The position is not simple, the position requires attention and attention to your interests, attention to the interests of the opponent.

58:25.000 --> 58:32.000
The position is called a compromiser, that is, a person looking for a compromise in the issues that are discussed in negotiations.

58:33.000 --> 58:38.000
It is important to remember that a compromise is not always a good thing for your country.

58:39.000 --> 58:45.000
It is important to remember that any compromise brings partiality, brings imperfection, a failure to achieve the result you wanted.

58:46.000 --> 58:52.000
But if this is an option that we accept, which we provide for you, then your role can be exactly this,

58:53.000 --> 58:57.000
a search for the middle ground, a search for compromises in all the issues that you discuss.

58:58.000 --> 59:05.000
It is important to understand that your role is most often and most likely depends on the goal that you set for the negotiations.

59:06.000 --> 59:09.000
Choose a role according to the goal of your negotiations.

59:10.000 --> 59:13.000
Any negotiations begin with mutual clarification of positions.

59:14.000 --> 59:21.000
It is clear that before the start of negotiations, the approximate position of the negotiator of the country that opposes you is clear.

59:21.000 --> 59:28.000
It is still important to clarify the current position for today, for now, for this time, this day, this place.

59:29.000 --> 59:32.000
The clarification of positions is carried out by asking questions.

59:33.000 --> 59:42.000
We ask, clarifying what is important to us, what is important for us to understand, before we start acting in the negotiation process, seeking to make our decision.

59:43.000 --> 59:45.000
What questions can be used?

59:45.000 --> 59:48.000
As a rule, everything starts with open questions.

59:49.000 --> 59:56.000
Open questions are questions that do not provide a clear answer, but offer to express themselves, start a discussion,

59:57.000 --> 01:00:01.000
open up a conversation that helps both sides clarify their positions.

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:11.000
Open questions can start with words like, what do you think about, or what is your opinion on this and that, what would you say about this and that.

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:18.000
Often, to start a business conversation, a topic that has nothing to do with the topic of negotiations is used.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:27.000
A so-called small conversation is concluded, in which both sides share some news that has nothing to do with the topic of the meeting.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:34.000
And then, some of the parties make a logical transition, make a bridge to the topic that is important to both.

01:00:35.000 --> 01:00:41.000
In this case, open questions allow to start this discussion, to start the discussion that is important to both sides.

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:45.000
Then, in the negotiation process, closed questions can also be used.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:52.000
Closed questions offer a clear, unambiguous answer, yes or no.

01:00:53.000 --> 01:01:03.000
Closed questions allow to determine the position that each side occupies in the negotiation process, when it is important to do this and get a meaningful, accurate answer, yes or no.

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:13.000
Questions can also have an alternative nature, when we offer to accept one of the two options we offer, either this or that.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:19.000
How do you think, you could take this position or that position?

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:22.000
How do you think, this option or that option will suit you?

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:34.000
We offer two options, two alternatives, and our partner can choose the option that is most suitable for him in this matter.

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:48.000
Questions can have a counter-nature, and in this case, they are a way to intercept the initiative, when we need to take control of the negotiation process, when we need to take control of the negotiation process.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:59.000
Counter-questions are questions that we ask in the same topic, as the questioner has been offered, but have a nature of clarification, clarification or detail.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:06.000
We ask a counter-question, giving it a clarification, otherwise it will have a too confrontational nature.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:19.000
If we do not need this, we ask a clarification question, explaining why we are asking this question, what purpose we are asking it for, and what we want to clarify, clarify, clarify for ourselves with its help.

01:02:19.000 --> 01:02:23.000
Questions that do not require an answer can also be used in negotiations.

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:42.000
Rhetorical questions are used to confirm or emphasize your attitude to any question, to emphasize your position, or to start some logical block or to complete such a block, summing up what has already been said.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:46.000
The main thing to remember is that the types of questions can be used in different ways.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:54.000
First, it is important to remember what result you want to come to, asking these questions and clarifying the position of your partner.

01:02:55.000 --> 01:03:04.000
It is important for us to understand what we should work with in the negotiation process, what is the position of the other party, what opinion is expressed with the partner on a particular question.

01:03:05.000 --> 01:03:07.000
A variety of types of questions help to do this.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:20.000
When communicating with your partner, it is important to remember that he requires constant attention to our side, and it is important for us to confirm this attention and also to express our attention to the words that the opponent says.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:24.000
For this, you can use the so-called active listening techniques.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:38.000
Even if the speech has the character of a monologue and your partner is speaking, talking about something important to him, we can give this monologue the character of a dialogue using the active listening technique.

01:03:39.000 --> 01:03:47.000
There are several simple techniques that allow us to participate in a conversation without stress and without saying a minimum of words with maximum participation.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:52.000
The simplest and most easily used technique is the mirror technique.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:04:12.000
When we listen to each phrase of our opponent, our partner in a conversation, we simply return the last words of this phrase in a monologue, returning them in the form of a mirror, confirming that we hear, listen and pay attention to what our opponent says.

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:26.000
If we want, we can continue this phrase in our own way, starting with the words that we heard from the opponent, hearing from the partner in a conversation, making a logical transition to our speech from the phrase of the partner.

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:44.000
We can also ask a clarifying question, clarifying something from what our opponent said, showing some detail, showing some aspect of the problem, clarifying some nuances of the topic that is being discussed in the negotiations.

01:04:45.000 --> 01:04:56.000
Or we can ask a question for understanding, using a paraphrase, using a rephrasing of the question, using our interpretation of understanding of what our opponent is saying.

01:04:56.000 --> 01:05:03.000
A paraphrase also helps us shift the focus of the conversation to the topic that is most beneficial to us.

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:18.000
We can ask a question for understanding, proposing our interpretation, and having received confirmation from the opponent that such an interpretation is accepted by them, we can continue the conversation with a new understanding of the issue, continue it with a new focus on the topic.

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:34.000
Also, the active listening technique is a technique of summing up the results, when we sum up the intermediate result of what the partner said, as if concluding his speech, summing up everything they said and suggesting to agree on the understanding of this issue.

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:51.000
Summing up the result, we conclude the conversation so that it does not go in a circle, for example, we say, so we talked about this, about this and about this, the conclusion is this, we sum up the results, on this topic we have reached such an agreement or reached an agreement in such a position.

01:05:51.000 --> 01:06:03.000
Another way to sum up the intermediate result is logical inference. In the case when we summed up the results, we addressed what was already said and summarized what we heard from our partner.

01:06:04.000 --> 01:06:16.000
In the case when we sum up the results, expressing logical inference, we take a step forward, we kind of assume what could have happened, what consequence could have come from what was said to our opponents.

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:29.000
We offer our interpretation of the conclusion from what was said to the partners in the negotiations. Logical inference allows us to agree on the conclusions we have made and achieve an understanding from both sides of these conclusions.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:39.000
The main thing that allows you to do active listening techniques is to have an initiative in negotiations in the case when we need to take over this initiative.

